<Time>1600795954132< /Time>< review>
I called Automotive Mediocrity for three things, one of which was a broken air conditioner. They couldn't get me in for a couple of weeks - which is fine - and I decided to wait it out in spite of the 110 degree heat wave. The morning of September 1st finally came and I brought it in to get it fixed. They said they needed a couple of hours to run diagnostics and then would call me with an estimate. They didn't call until after hours, which is also fine. I learned that they had additional diagnostics that they needed to do which would take about an hour and would I like to schedule that for September 10th - 10 days later- their next available spot, after which they would know what was wrong and could then schedule work to be done.

Wait, what? I brought my car in to get it fixed, not schedule more diagnostics for 10 days out only then to be able to schedule it to be fixed?
The guy who I spoke with treated me like I was nuts to expect that when I bring my car in to get it fixed it was... wait for it... to get it fixed. I felt like I was getting gaslighted.

I found a different mechanic pretty quickly and told Automotive Malignant that I was coming to get my car. They indicated that they needed to put the front bumper and other parts back on, first, because they had to remove them for diagnostics. Fine. After paying $260 I drove my car from Automotive Inimical to the new mechanic and the front right side of the car sounded like it was dragging and about to fall off. I was scared to death. I don't know if they intentionally or negligently did not put the car back together correctly but either are equally awful. When I got to the mechanic he verified it wasn't secured properly (at all?) and recommended I take it back to have it done at no charge but I said I would rather pay than have that guy gaslight me again and treat my like I was nuts to think there was anything wrong.</review>

Got the it back and found the noise still present. Took it back, was told the AC lines were making contact with the body or firewall. Got it back noise is still there but as loud. < text>
Highly suggest not going here! Im a fan of getting a business a chance to correct itself but these people have no clue on making customers happy and didnt try.

So, per a friends recommendation I went in there at 10am yesterday for a smog check. Price was reasonable, job got done and at the time I thought everything was A ok. So I decided I would come back that afternoon and get an oil change . Thing is I would found out later that the first job they didnt do correct.

Funny thing is I met with a client told them I had to hurry our appointment as I was going there after to get an oil change. He was a good guy and seemed to know the area and advised me not to go there. He told me the place was known for upsales on everyone that comes in. Well I didnt take his advice and went in anyways to my appointment at 4pm.

Got there at 15 minutes to 4pm they advised me that my car would be ready in 45 minutes to an hour tops.

One hour later....still waiting in loby. I go the counter service man advices me they are pulling it now.

One hour and 15 minutes later....still not done. The owner sees me frustrated and comes up to me and says she will check it out, I tell her I need to go to a dinner date.

Owner comes back and has a tray says my fuilds are dirty, coolant, rear diff fluid, transmission fluid and more. Thus upselling begins find out later that they do this to mostly everyone. She then mentiones other problems I inform her again I need to get going.

Finally almost wo hours later my car is outside. I immediately notice oil smear marks on the side of my car, and when I open the door notice oil on the seat on the door hinge snd more! I start trying to clean when the guy that did the oil change comes out and aplogized saying his hands where dirty and he was rushed. Well it was so bad I went in tor a towel inside to clean up.

Owner asks me whats wrong I inform her of the oil mess and that I wasnt happy with time issue. She immediately goes on the defensive tells me now one of my lug nuts was to blame as it took extra time to take off. She then tells me im a liar basically by saying she saw the guys hands and watched him wash his hands. However, she did not know that moments earlier he had apologized for it and admitted to it. So I tell her finally your guy came out and admitted to it and aplogized . She then says says how sorry she is and that if he is doing this she would fire him. She hands me a wet paper towel and helps me clean up the mess. No other offer for this horrible service was given and I had to help clean up a mess that should have never happened.

So....I finally drive away hoping this is the only set of problems hopefully. I get on the road and notice im now on empty!!! I pull over to get gas and notice my locked gas cap cover is not on and is actually on its side where the hole is. Well I know I wasnt on empty before I got there and I have ocd about my gas cap. So I drive back the shop and talk to another man which may had been the other owner.  I tell him im not accusing him specifically but I know I didnt do the gas cap and that it wasn't on empty before I got there, he tells me he watched them do it and nothing fradulent was done. I was nice and said was there any reason they may have unlocked my gas cap he said no. I then asked being lifted is it possible because its a truck that it showed less gas then there was?

He stated no way possible.  I told him I was upset and would leave a review. When talking to a friend they told me most likely that when they did the smog earlier that day on the first job they opened the gas cap and then ignored putting it back on right. So thats a possible senciero.

Either way, a two hour oil change, oil all over the car and seat, the extreme upselling,  and gas cap and mystery gas disappearance im beyond dissatisfied.  I highly recommend choosing and reading reviews before going here. Appears im not the only one with problems here. This is also the longest review ive left on here thus expressing my frustration .<//text>

< text>
We did the Ultimate Tasting Experience and had a great time with Liam (one of the owners). The wines were great, and they had brie, crackers, and prosciutto to go alongside everything. It was fun to try so many wines from the barrel (they offer "futures" to purchase some wines in advance of their production, which we did not do). <review>Came here with some friends after running the Cloverdale half marathon, boy is it a beautiful property.  The parking situation is a bit strange, they don't have any designated spaces except on handicap space.  So you either have to park along side the driveway or do what most people do and back in between the vines.  The tasting experience here was very pleasant, thankfully our friends are club members so we were able to relax down by the pool.
The staff made it feel more like a hangout than a proper tasting which was really nice.  We were able to just take our time and enjoy the wine, the property, and the company.  The wines were all pretty enjoyable, but were a bit too light for my taste.  We didn't end up purchasing any bottles this time, but would consider buying some in the future.  One of the strangest things to me was that to join the wine club didn't offer any discounts on the wine.  It was more like they are trying to sell a membership to their property instead of focusing on the wine.  Definitely would be worth joining if you are a local, or within an hour or so.  But, for someone like me who enjoys buying and aging wine it didn't seem like a good sell.<//review><user_name>Nathan Delaney<//user_name>< gmap_id>

<time>1532904538355</time><Rate>3<//Rate>< text>
RIP Christopher Creek as we knew it. We came here years ago when CC was still under the original ownership. Back then we were absolutely impressed by the personable service, the friendly low key atmosphere and the Cab. Well, several years later although the buildings are the same, the wine and atmosphere is not. Although the guys working the tasting room were friendly and the wine was okay, we were underwhelmed and the prices are ridiculous. We met one of the new owners, who had quite a snobbish air about him. They seem to be all about pushing membership and catering towards the members only. We left there feeling disappointed, like this winery has turned into a money grab more typical of the Napa wineries. They were out of the Cab, too.< /text>

<text>Always have the DOUNT I want in.<//text><user_id>116884579579215740591</user_id></record>
</dataset><record>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
Better Be Donuts has the freshest baked goods: from light and fluffy glazed donuts to delicious cake donuts and delectable apple fritters, as well as other standard donut selections - they even have ham and cheese filled croissants that are better than the ones from Starbucks. They are open at 5:30 am 7 days a week and close at 9:00 pm every day except Sunday when they close at 8:30 pm.

I usually visit once a week and try to go first thing in the morning when the donuts are freshest and still a bit warm. On a few occasions when I was unable to stop in the morning I called ahead and asked to have my order pre-packed for pick up anytime up until closing, thus ensuring I would have my weekly doughnut fix.

The employees are well mannered, attentive, and are quick to help. But be warned; these doughnuts are so good that by closing time there is little selection left from which to choose.  If you can't go until late, it's best to call ahead to pre order.< /Review>

<date>1572823322311<//date><Rating>2<//Rating>< review>
Nice guys but overpriced products and services.   I purchased a brand new bike on-line and took it to Irvine Bicycles to assemble. The bike was practically built already except for the dropper post, which required internal cabling, and the front disc brake to be installed.   They charged me the full pro-build price of $250 for a boxed bike.  This is not a frame-up build. I knew that was pricey, but I did agree to it only because I did not want to bother shopping around.  They gave me a free 30-day adjustment period.

I went back to the shop about a month later for adjustments.  Frank said the 30-day did not apply because I changed out components.  I had changed the rear derailleur because I bent it on my first ride off-road. I had to get a new tire because the tube blew and it blew out the tire beads.  I also changed the handlebar and stem to fit me better.    I did not modify the hydraulic brake system.

I totally understand why the 30-day did not apply because it was like rebuilding the bike, but then again‚Ä¶‚Ä¶they charged me $250 assembly for a boxed bike that was practically built already.   I would have appreciated it if they can install the new oval chainring I bought (by the way, I highly recommend the oval chainring). Frank was going to charge me $45 to install the oval chainring.   I knew that was pricey, so I declined.  I left the bike for them to ‚Äúlook it over‚Äù.

I picked up my bike later that day and took it another local bike shop to install the chainring.  $15 and  10 minutes later I was enjoying my newly installed chainring  (by the way, the Truvativ Stylo crank was easy to take off to install the chainring; catch it on YouTube).

The point I want to make is‚Ä¶‚Ä¶shop around.  In fact, on a couple of occasions before I bought my bike on-line, I had gone to Irvine Bicycles but the prices were too high.  I know it‚Äôs tough being a local bike shop on pricing, but it‚Äôs all about building relationships.  I‚Äôm not here to tell Irvine bicycles how to run their shop. I really wanted Irvine Bicycles to be my ‚Äúgo-to‚Äù shop for my cycling needs, but based on my experience, the pricing and relationship just isn‚Äôt there.< /review>

They have good product/inventory but it is not logically presented. Could use a big and effective re-organization.<//text>< Pics>

<review>Avoid Frank, if you can. He is the one with glasses trying to sell you something, but never working on the bikes.

The mechanics are generally knowledgeable and helpful.  When I'm lucky enough to drop in while Frank is away, the experience is good.

However, I've had repeat experiences to the point that I now peek just to see whether Frank is behind the register.

He once made a major fuss over me trying to use a credit card to pay for a $40 purchase. Seriously if its that important to save the fractional service charge for cc processing when you're already charging full MSRP on basic accessories, you might be doing something wrong.

Today I had the misfortune of listening to Frank try to up-sell an old man a new tire for his "value class" mtb which he brought in for a simple flat fix. The tires showed age, but little actual wear. Frank didn't even inspect the tire for damage / puncture debris which, if found, might justify replacement.  He immediately turned on the sales pressure. The man made it clear he was "old and broke" and his bike fit the bill.  This didn't dissuade Frank at all. "Save time and money if you replace both [tube and tire] now".

One time I asked Frank if he had glue for tubulars and he tried to sell me tufo tape. I clarified, "its for cylco-cross" and he continued to school me on how the high tire pressure paired with the tape... I all but lost it.

I happen to live around the corner and would prefer shopping locally, but with such experiences, its my last resort.< /review><pics>None<//pics>< resp>

<Review>Update:
Visited this location again and the soap quantity was perfect. Think it was just a fluke wash. Owner replied‚Äî(as seen) and I‚Äôll look forward to AMEX maybe becoming available one day. I have updated my review to (5) stars!

Review:
I have been searching all over for a Self-Service Car Wash that accepts credit cards. This establishment accepts Visa, Mastercard, and Discover and it's a pretty simple system to use. I used my Visa card tonight and paid $5 for a 12min car wash that I was presently surprised with. I will say the High-Pressure Soap didn‚Äôt start spraying suds until about 60+ sec. and was not as sudsy as I expected but it did get the job done. My vehicle was moderately dirty from the recent rainfall in SoCal.

Things I liked:
- Ability to use Credit Cards: Visa, Mastercard, and Discover
- DO NOT take away Credit Cards abilities, please!
- High powered "triggered" blower was AMAZING and nothing like I have seen in a Self-Service Car wash before.
- High-Pressure Sprayer has good water pressure and excellent wide spray angle

Things I feel need Improvement:

A really scary part from a human aspect. The reality is, this part sit in between the Norwalk city service yard ,and a grade school . Surrounded by factories. The best part, most days you'll find an amazing assortment people , ranging in the unlawful septum of human exsistence. They have a children's activity center here for summer events. The ambience was great, the drinks were superb, and the service was A1. My friends and I ordered the beer flight, and my favorite was the chai IPA. It was earthy, caffeinated, and had the right amount of chai. If I could get a whole keg of it, I would!

This place is definitely a great weeknight hangout. They have outdoor and indoor seating, and the decorations are simple, yet impactful. I absolutely recommend going here for a drink or a small treat!< /Text>

< Text>
Awesome cider! However, know that the food is not  worth ordering. We ordered a few flights of ciders and were all impressed, but the table agreed the real winner of the night was there non-alcoholic cider option. It was incredible.

The food was lackluster, to say the least. High prices (~$16-18) for our entrees (burger, risotto, fish and chips) and charcuterie board. Servings were small, but not quite delicious. No one left pleased with their meal.< /Text>

<Review>Gorgeous space for upscale cider tasting experience, with artisanal ciders sourced globally.  Exquisite attention to detail from stone laced bar stools carried through to stone tap handles encasing slices of apple inside.  Fantastic, creative brunch menu to die for too with Egg Cochon poached egg over pulled pork, bread pudding and gochujang coated crispy potatoes, super fragrant Fried Rice with crab and spam.  Love this place so much, I consider it worth the drive from LA to SD many times over.<//Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOoFa4odLCjd2Un7iF3tCplRUNtAs_sBD9BVDOI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOy6KDCmwaEJAupBFk4eKVv4LpbHpKMB35zk56A=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP1gSroPhquZE70ziodXqTFlHH978fXOeCoFcND=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPE9JJksglT1WcvDER6CKLQsy2lLW6ZRGMXaQ3f=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNhh_hFucv4zL8OfL7FDrmbGovEJWdxQvKyqoFP=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN8M57h8G1Y401p_M3zQ5EnGny4HQ7xUgdGO_JV=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPkkdaWKh3KoNPVatObGEYsXhzwzO2uzg7zoiht=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><resp>None< /resp>< GmapID>

< review>
I really enjoyed the ciders last night. We visited this place when they opened, was really disappointed and didn't go back. We visited another great cidery in the area, Serpentine, and they told us to give Bivouac another chance. I'm really glad we did. We had 2 flights each, and was able to navigate their whole line up. We did not have one that was disappointing. From prickly pear to strawberry ginger, they all tasted great. I ended the night with an Ube Pina Colada mixed cocktail and was very impressed! We really appreciated the staff and the drinks. We didn't eat, but now will definitely be back for dinner as well.< /review>

< text>
Bivouac is a new ciderworks in the heart of North Park, which is craft beer heaven. They do have beer at Bivouac, but they are known for their cider. I don't often drink cider because I imagine it as a super sweet drink. Not the case at all! I had three different fry ciders that weren't sweet at all, just delicious!  The food is also excellent. Great wings, the clam chowder was more like steamed muscles (but clams) in a delicious sauce. The Patty melt, hummus and poke were all wonderful. Great place!<//text>

**Update: Liquor license granted, pouring from 23 January.
---
They're waiting on their liquor license, but don't let that stop you going for an amazing lunch. The burger is fantastic, their special ketchup is my new addiction, and they have plenty on the menu for vegans too. The fries are ultra thin and crispy, with just the right amount of garlic and parsley. The interior decor is gorgeous and clever, the vibe is classy and casual. Lara and the rest of the staff are great. Can't wait for their full opening!</review>

< name>
Brijet Myers< /name>
< Time>
1533147182488</Time>
<rate>5< /rate>< text>
This new-ish place in my neighborhood is an absolute gem. The design is incredible, and I would come hang out here even if the food and drinks sucked- which they do not. I've tried almost all the ciders they offer currently and have not been disappointed by one. I love that they have dry, less sweet ciders. I wasn't expecting to be wowed by the food at a place known for the drinks, but all I can say is get the 'tongue and cheek nachos'. One of the top ten best dishes I've had in my life.
I love their commitment to using locally sourced food as well.

The service is really great in that "very friendly but not annoying" way. Hosts, bartenders, servers, bussers- everyone was smiling and helpful and honestly that is sadly hard to come by in restaurants these days.

Bivouac is now one of my favorite places to go on a date, with girlfriends, or take clients to for a hip atmosphere and delicious dinner. I wish I could just eat there every day.<//text>

<username>Jay Shriver< /username><Time>1582331878786</Time><review>Edit to my below review ... I had another business trip to San Diego this week. I stopped at Bivouac and was hugely disappointed. The ciders tasted flavorless and watered down (another reviewer noted the same thing and she's right, even though I initially refused to believe it). Rumor has it they changed cider makers. Stay away, Serpentine is more of a drive but a much much better product.

Old review:
I love ciders. When I travel I look for cider houses to visit. On a recent work trip to San Diego I thought I wouldn't get a chance to visit Bivouac but a 4 hour delay in my Southwest flight gave me the window of opportunity I needed to visit. After a bus ride and some walking I arrived around 2 pm on a Friday afternoon. The first thing I noticed was the decor, I can see it being a popular place to socialize and enjoy some adult beverages. I took a seat at the bar near the window that opens onto 30th street. The bartender was sweet and very helpful. After discussing the flavors with her I had a flight of the Savoy, San Diego Jam and Hunter's Bend, and all were delicious. I also had a pint of the San Diego Jam and a pint of a Transom/Albright blend suggested by the bartender. All were very enjoyable. I also enjoyed talking to the owner Matt, he's a friendly guy who was very easy to talk to. I wanted to stay longer but it was time to call Uber and head off to the airport for my flight. I had a great time and would definitely go back!<//review>< Rating>
1<//Rating>

<Pics>None< /Pics>< userid>
100900010911970750562</userid>
< review>
Bivouac is a new, rather unique restaurant and bar that specializes in their own house made cider with alcohol.  The place looks brand new with gorgeous furnishings(I got to sit at a booth with seats suspended from the ceiling that rock...fun).

There is a full bar and restaurant seating.

I had the cider flight consisting of 4 glasses ranging from apple to currant which was my favorite.  The cider is made in large, brand new, very cool looking distilling vats on the premises(that I photographed).

I ordered mussels and their signature "Impossible Burger" with shoestring fries and remoulade.

The mussels are top quality PEI(prince edward island canada) and were plump and exceedingly delicious in the buttery broth.

The burger was cooked perfectly to my specifications with gouda cheese on top and was so tasty; I award it best burger I've had so far this year.

Service by Owner Matt and server Anna was 1st rate.  Matt went over the selections with me and explained some interesting facts about the cider making process.

Bivouac is my favorite restaurant/ bar in North Park now...not bad for only being 8 weeks young.< /review>
< rating>
5<//rating>

I love the vibes of this place and it's in a great area....I am going to move to San Diego just so I can eat here every Friday night</Review>

Located in a decent location right off the highway, convenient for those that commute ( right here üòÅ‚úå).  The homeless population is a bit high in the area as well. Nevertheless I recieved my food in a decent time and sat down to eat.  The seating areas are nice, gotta give them that. I also witnessed a lady order an iced coffee, right behind me and about 4 people were served before her.   2 stars for access off freeway, the food being hot and speedy, and seating arrangement. Always an interesting place.  For dine-in they give the number on the receipt aswell as a delivery number to srt on the table.  So I ask "will the good be delivered to the table?" Yes, they said.
